subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Service
object: Examples include a photocopying service, a banking service, an authentication service, interlibrary loans, a Z39.50 or Web server.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/MovingImage
object: A series of visual representations imparting an impression of motion when shown in succession.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Text
object: Examples include books, letters, dissertations, poems, newspapers, articles, archives of mailing lists. Note that facsimiles or images of texts are still of the genre Text.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Image
object: A visual representation other than text.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Event
object: Metadata for an event provides descriptive information that is the basis for discovery of the purpose, location, duration, and responsible agents associated with an event. Examples include an exhibition, webcast, conference, workshop, open day, performance, battle, trial, wedding, tea party, conflagration.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Image
object: Examples include images and photographs of physical objects, paintings, prints, drawings, other images and graphics, animations and moving pictures, film, diagrams, maps, musical notation.  Note that Image may include both electronic and physical representations.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/InteractiveResource
object: A resource requiring interaction from the user to be understood, executed, or experienced.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Dataset
object: Examples include lists, tables, and databases.  A dataset may be useful for direct machine processing.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/PhysicalObject
object: Note that digital representations of, or surrogates for, these objects should use Image, Text or one of the other types.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Collection
object: A collection is described as a group; its parts may also be separately described.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/InteractiveResource
object: Examples include forms on Web pages, applets, multimedia learning objects, chat services, or virtual reality environments.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Software
object: Examples include a C source file, MS-Windows .exe executable, or Perl script.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Sound
object: Examples include a music playback file format, an audio compact disc, and recorded speech or sounds.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/StillImage
object: Examples include paintings, drawings, graphic designs, plans and maps. Recommended best practice is to assign the type Text to images of textual materials. Instances of the type Still Image must also be describable as instances of the broader type Image.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Service
object: A system that provides one or more functions.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Software
object: A computer program in source or compiled form.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/PhysicalObject
object: An inanimate, three-dimensional object or substance.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Dataset
object: Data encoded in a defined structure.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Sound
object: A resource primarily intended to be heard.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/Text
object: A resource consisting primarily of words for reading.

subject: http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/MovingImage
object: Examples include animations, movies, television programs, videos, zoetropes, or visual output from a simulation.  Instances of the type Moving Image must also be describable as instances of the broader type Image.
